## LLM build scripts you can drop into your course generator

Use one per module. Replace bracketed items before running.

### Script M3.1 — Data Types and Structures

> Role: You are a pedagogy-aware course builder.
> Inputs: outline for Module 3.1, learner profile, target tools.
> Goal: produce interactive text, narrated slides outline, audio dialog script, a mind map, 10 adaptive questions, and a hands-on lab.
> Constraints: follow Learn Your Way’s multi-representation pattern with embedded questions and immediate feedback. Cite docs where applicable.
> Deliver:
>
> 1. Interactive text with 6 checkpoints.
> 2. Slide outline with speaker notes.
> 3. Audio dialog script that surfaces misconceptions about keys and nulls.
> 4. Mind map JSON for nodes and edges.
> 5. Ten adaptive MCQs with rationales and difficulty tiers.
> 6. Lab brief that culminates in a schema sketch and data dictionary starter using minimal metadata elements.

### Script M3.2 — SQL Fundamentals

> Inputs: sample schema plus retail dataset.
> Produce:
> • Progressive SQL tasks that align to `SELECT`, filtering, joins, `GROUP BY`, and simple subqueries. Ground syntax in mainstream docs and include runnable solutions. ([PostgreSQL][3])
> • Auto-grader test cases and error hints.
> • Join visualizer prompts and examples.
> • Two mini-projects that answer stakeholder questions, each with a short written justification.

### Script M3.3 — Spreadsheet Mastery

> Produce:
> • Guided workbook plan with tabs for raw data, pivot, formulas, and results.
> • A pivot build checklist consistent with Google Sheets and Excel references. ([Google for Developers][4])
> • Ten quick tasks that verify formula correctness and pivot configuration.

### Script M3.4 — Data Collection and Metadata

> Produce:
> • Scenario-based items for SRS, stratified, cluster, and systematic sampling, each with “when to use” guidance and a short computation. ([PennState: Statistics Online Courses][5])
> • A one-page sampling plan template.
> • A minimal metadata template informed by ICPSR guidance, including title, description, variables, units, coverage, method, caveats, and provenance. ([ICPSR][6])

---

## Instructor delivery notes

• Keep every lesson multi-modal and adaptive. Google’s Learn Your Way emphasizes embedded questions, narrated slides, audio dialogs, and mind maps, all adapted by level and interest. ([Google Research][1])
• Use widely available datasets. Superstore is bundled with Tableau and documented by Tableau’s help pages, which prevents dead links. ([Tableau Help][10])
• When teaching pivots, reference the official product docs so platform differences are clear. ([Google for Developers][4])

